im <- load.image('group_4.jpg')
plot(im)

img_g<-grayscale(im)
plot(img_g)

hist(img_g)

mean_std_of_rows<-array(0,dim = c(400,2))
mean_std_of_columns<-array(0,dim = c(400,2))
for (i in c(1:400)) {
  mean_std_of_rows[i,]<-c(mean(img_g[i,]),sqrt(var(img_g[i,])))
  mean_std_of_columns[i,]<-c(mean(img_g[,i]),sqrt(var(img_g[,i])))
}

We constructed 2 Dimensional array for mean and std values of rows and columns
We collected each row and colunm means and std value in this 2 dimensional array
First column of this array gives the mean values
Second column of this array gives the std values for each sample.

mean_std_of_columns<-data.frame(mean_std_of_columns)
mean_std_of_rows<-data.frame(mean_std_of_rows)
bounds<-c(0.4,1.2)

We plotted the control charts for the first 2 row as an example.Because the number of rows is too large ,we didn’t plot all of them.

par(mfrow = c(1,2))
plot(img_g[,1],type = "line",ylim = bounds,ylab = "Pixel values",xlab ="Column numbers in the first row")+
  abline(h=mean_std_of_rows[1,1]+3*mean_std_of_rows[1,2],col="blue") +
  abline(h=mean_std_of_rows[1,1]-3*mean_std_of_rows[1,2],col="blue") + 
  abline(h=mean_std_of_rows[1,1],col="red")

We know that in the X bar Charts;
UCL = mean(Xbar) + K * sigma(s)
LCL = mean(Xbar) - K * sigma(s)

These are the X bar charts for pixel values in the first 2 rows. We assumed K=3 so,we constructed 3 sigma limit control chart for these 2 charts and also others.

image_new_for_rows<-img_g

for(i in c(1:400)){
  UCL<-mean_std_of_rows[i,1]+3*mean_std_of_rows[i,2]
  LCL<-mean_std_of_rows[i,1]-3*mean_std_of_rows[i,2]
  for(j in c(1:400)){
    if((img_g[j,i]<LCL) || (img_g[j,i]> UCL)){
      image_new_for_rows[j,i]<-0
    }
  }
}

X bar Chart

par(mfrow = c(1,2))
plot(1:2, type='n',main = "New Image")
rasterImage(image_new_for_rows, 1, 1, 2, 2)
plot(1:2, type='n',main = "Original Image")
rasterImage(img_g, 1, 1, 2, 2)

When we look at our image, we can see that there are some shapes that are distributed with a specific form.Actually the ways of these shapes are really important in this project.We investigated the image rows by rows in the first part and rearranged the pixel values of the image according to 3 sigma control limits.As we expected when we look at a specific row, control limits become dependent to the pixel values of only that specific row.Therefore the shapes that seems out of control in the overall image may be inside of the control limits according to their rows.The reason of this situation is that the mean values of each rows are not the same and their standart deviations are different from each other.As a consequence,we can say that the pixel values that are out of control affected by the horizontal distributions of the corresponding pixels.

CONTROL CHARTS FOR THE FIRST TWO COLUMN

image_new_for_columns<-img_g
for(i in c(1:400)){
  UCL<-mean_std_of_columns[i,1]+3*mean_std_of_columns[i,2]
  LCL<-mean_std_of_columns[i,1]-3*mean_std_of_columns[i,2]
  for(j in c(1:400)){
    if((img_g[i,j]<LCL) || (img_g[i,j]> UCL)){
      image_new_for_columns[j,i]<-0
    }
  }
}
par(mfrow = c(1,2))
plot(1:2, type='n',main = "New Image")
rasterImage(image_new_for_columns, 1, 1, 2, 2)
plot(1:2, type='n',main = "Original Image")
rasterImage(img_g, 1, 1, 2, 2)

We investigated the image columns by columns in the second part and rearranged the pixel values of the image according to 3 sigma control limits.As we expected when we look at a specific column, control limits become dependent to the pixel values of only that specific column.Because the mean and std values of columns are different from each other,we can say that the pixel values that are out of control affected by the vertical distributions of the corresponding pixels.However,the most important thing in here is the ways of the sapes on the image.The directions of the shapes are generally from top to bottom of the image and this really affects the std and mean values of columns and rows.Because of this reason,performing row operation gives much more out of control pixels according to the column operation.
